Jason Rogers wrote:

&gt; I have often found that there are other ways around using reflection in
&gt; Java.  The Adaptor pattern for instance is a simple way of implementing
&gt; the Pluggable Selector.  It will respond to refactorings, it doesn&#39;t add
&gt; much complexity, and it&#39;s efficient.

Really? How does Adapter do this? Specifically, I was working in an area 
where there were a number of rule methods, like

     boolean isReadyToStart();
     boolean isX();
     boolean isY();

and there was one big method that essentially did this:

     if (isReadyToStart() && isX() && isY() && ... ) {
         doTheCoolThing();
     }

Now there /is/ an obvious refactoring here, to use &quot;inject&quot; which might 
now be part of Commons Collections, but which I ended up implementing 
some time ago.

     create a Predicate for each rule and add it to a rules Set

     Inject inject = new Inject(false) {
         public boolean result;

         public Inject(boolean startValue) {
             this.result = startValue;
         }

         public void process(Object input) {
             Predicate each = (Predicate) input;
             result = result && each.evaluate();
         }
     }


     CollectionUtils.forEachDo(rules, inject);

     if (inject.result) {
         doTheCoolThing();
     }

This is better: to add a new rule requires only adding a Predicate to 
the rules Set, but that probably means adding the boolean method, then 
wrapping it in a Predicate, or worse, littering the codebase with a 
bunch of top-level Predicate implementations that I can&#39;t read together 
at a glance. (They&#39;re often one-line methods, anyway!) I prefer to 
discover all the rules and use them. For this, I do what JUnit does: use 
a naming convention and collect all the rules into a ruleset and run 
them with the Inject closure. When I showed some well-known and 
well-meaning agilistas this, they uniformly thought I was nuts. Since 
they all use xUnit, I find that surprising.

Granted, in JDK 5.0 I would use annotations instead of reflection, but I 
don&#39;t plan to work much in JDK 5.0. If I wanted to write C++, I&#39;d write C++.
